{"questionId":"21952","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A manufacturer of chocolates produces them in individual packets, claiming to have an&nbsp;average of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>85</mn></math> chocolates per packet.</p>\n<p>Talha bought <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn></math> of these packets in order to check the manufacturer’s claim.</p>\n<p>Given that the number of individual chocolates is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>, Talha found that, from his <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn></math> packets,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Σ</mtext><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2506</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Σ</mtext><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>209</mn><mo> </mo><mn>738</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find an unbiased estimate for the mean number <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>μ</mi><mo>)</mo></math> of chocolates per packet.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>x</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mtext>Σ</mtext><mi>x</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2506</mn><mn>30</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>83</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>83</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5333</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><br>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"21952","referenceCode":"21M.1.AHL.TZ2.10a","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find an unbiased estimate for the mean number (μ) of chocolates per packet.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","AHL 4.14—Linear transformation of a single RV, E(X) and VAR(X), unbiased estimators","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","AHL 4.16—Confidence intervals"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}